<TITLE> Playwright Sayeed Ahmad dies </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 21 (bdnews24.com)  Sayeed Ahmad, playwright and teacher of Dhaka University's dramatics and music department, died on Thursday. He was 79. Ahmad died in the capital's Lab Aid Hospital at around 5:50am, Prof Israfil Shaheen of the dramatics department told bdnews24.com. The body was taken to his Lalmatia home from the hospital. The author and critic is most well-known for his plays Kalbela (1962), Milepost (1965), Trishnae (1968), Ek Din Protidin (1974) and Shesh Nawab (1988), which have been translated into English, French, German and Italian. His works focus on how man is able to confront and survive against the forces of nature and achieve co-existence. Ahmad, born on Jan 1, 1931 in Dhaka, received the Bangla Academy Award in 1975 and the French Legion d'Honneur in 1993. He worked in Eastern Service of BBC during the period 1954-56. He also delivered lectures at universities and theatre academies around the world, inlcuding Brazil, China, France, Germany, Holland, Hong Kong, India, Japan, Malaysia, Morocco, Norway, Thailand, Turkey, USA and USSR. bdn
